benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: POST /1.0/kb/catalog/xml - Upload the full catalog as XML

covered: Valid payload submissions and successful creation scenarios across TC01, TC02, TC03, TC11, TC13, TC24, TC28, TC31 demonstrating 201 creation with valid XML and appropriate headers (including required and optional headers).
Header and input validation coverage: TC06 (missing required header), TC07 (empty header), TC10 (invalid content type), TC09 (empty body), TC23 (whitespace-only payload).
Comprehensive error handling coverage: malformed XML (TC08), partially corrupted XML (TC18), invalid/malicious content (TC17), and service/network failure scenarios (TC16, TC15).
Large and boundary payloads: TC12 (very large payload), TC30 (boundary values).
Encoding and content variations: TC29 (UTF-8/UTF-16), TC28 (XML with comments/CDATA), TC24 (special characters).
Behavior with duplicates and idempotence: TC25 (duplicate catalog version).
Performance/scale testing: TC19 (normal load performance) and TC20 (concurrent load).
Regression and compatibility: TC21 (known bug regression), TC22 (backward compatibility).
gaps: Caching behavior and related headers (e.g., ETag, Cache-Control) are not tested.
Rate limiting/throttling scenarios are not covered.
Additional 500-level server error scenarios (beyond 503 for backend unavailability) are not explicitly tested.
Explicit, consistent validation of error message content across different failure cases could be strengthened.
Idempotency and transactional rollback scenarios are not specified.
recommendations: Add tests for caching headers and validation of cache-related behavior on POST responses.
Introduce rate limiting tests to verify handling under burst traffic.
Add tests for additional 500-level errors (e.g., database failure) to broaden server error coverage.
Standardize and broaden assertions for error messages across failure scenarios to ensure consistency.
Consider idempotency and rollback tests to verify behavior on repeated or failed submissions.
Enhance authorization edge-case coverage with varying token states and permissions beyond the basic 401/403 scenarios.
